## Issues & Recommendations

### 1. 🔴 Missing Body Parsing & Input Validation Middleware
The app has no body parser, which means any future POST/PUT routes won't be able to safely read request bodies. Add parsing with size limits to prevent denial-of-service via large payloads:

```js
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

// Limit body size to prevent DoS
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: true, limit: '10kb' }));
```

---

### 2. 🔴 No Security Headers
The app exposes default Express headers (e.g., `X-Powered-By: Express`), which leaks implementation details. Use `helmet` to set secure HTTP headers:

```bash
npm install helmet
```

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // Sets X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, CSP, etc.
```

---

### 3. 🟠 No Global Error Handler
Unhandled errors will cause Express to send verbose stack traces to clients. Add a centralized error handler:

```js
// 404 handler (place after all routes)
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
});

// General error handler (place last)
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack); // Log internally
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({
    error: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production'
      ? 'Internal server error'  // Don't leak details in production
      : err.message
  });
});
```

---

### 4. 🟠 No Rate Limiting
All routes are unprotected from brute-force or flooding attacks. Add rate limiting:

```bash
npm install express-rate-limit
```

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

const limiter = rateLimit({
  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes
  max: 100,                  // limit each IP to 100 requests per window
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
});

app.use(limiter);
```

---

### 5. 🟡 `/users` Exposes Static Data with No Auth
Even as a demo, returning user data (especially emails) without any authentication check is a bad habit to establish:

```js
// Example: simple API key guard middleware
function requireApiKey(req, res, next) {
  const key = req.headers['x-api-key'];
  if (!key || key !== process.env.API_KEY) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
  }
  next();
}

app.get('/users', requireApiKey, (req, res) => {
  // ...
});
```

---

### 6. 🟡 Hardcoded Port
The port `3000` is hardcoded. Use an environment variable with a fallback:

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

---

### 7. 🟡 No Request Logging
Without logging, security incidents are invisible. Consider `morgan` for request logs:

```bash
npm install morgan
```

```js
const morgan = require('morgan');
app.use(morgan('combined')); // Use 'combined' for production-style logs
```

---

